framework: sense of belonging and CS science identity
Implications_list:
The diversity gaps in computer science represent a potential waste of untapped
talent among large sectors of the population. National economic growth, innovation, security, and international competition require sufficient numbers of trained members of the scientific and technical workforce. Increasing the participation of underrepresented groups in CS is widely expected to reduce labor supply shortages, create better products for an increasingly diverse national and global customer base, and foster creativity and innovation through the inclusion of diverse teams and perspectives.

But beyond meeting short- and long-term human capital demands, closing diversity
gaps also has a distributive justice dimension. Reducing diversity gaps will increase opportunities for social mobility for women, lower-income youth, and members of underserved minority groups. The lack of CS skills and/or credentials among under-represented groups limits their access to high paying jobs in the tech sector. Thus, narrowing the diversity gaps in the field has implications for addressing the occupational and income inequality among the US population.

Title: Using the S-STEM Programmatic Lens to Investigate Equity in a Computer Science Department
Author: Hug
RQ_list:
1. How did S-STEM student outcomes compare with their peersâ€™ outcomes in computer science at UNIV? 
2. How do student outcomes differ due to effects of sexism and racism in computer science at UNIV? 
3. How do financial and familial educational differences influence student outcomes in computer science at UNIV? 
4. How can the department incorporate statistical findings into improved, more equitable educational practice?
framework: Sociocultural Learning Theory & Critical Race Theory
Implications_list:
This study emerged from an S-STEM scholarship program 
at UNIV, and was intended to do the following: a) understand 
how social identifiers including gender, ethnicity/race, familial 
income, transfer status, and familial experiences with higher 
education constrain and afford student success, b) reframe 
comparative success outcomes in critical terms, as evidence of 
sexism and racism and other forms of inequity, rather than as 
deficits in students; and c) hypothesize factors that may 
influence S-STEM student success, based on complimentary 
qualitative data.

Title: Proven professional development strategies: Data from an eng transfer student scholarship-projects-mentoring success program
Author: Rodriguez
RQ_list: How can 4-year institutions best prepare engineering and computer science students (hereafter denoted ENG) for the many opportunities and challenges that they may encounter as they progress into their junior and senior years?
Implications_list:
More specifically, future work will address (1) how to more effectively determine individual student (high/low context, learning, mentoring) needs, helping them get started and determining their next step, (2) helping students 
to more concretely relate classes, projects and internships to future goals, (3) deploying more team assignments to encourage networking, (4) helping students find suitable mentors and help strengthen mentor-mentee connections, (5) assisting students with choosing a technical area and formulating a project problem, (6) helping students research companies and acquiring skills sought in job postings, (7) helping students prepare for opportunities before them (e.g. funded/paid FURI/REU projects, senior design, internships, graduate school, fellowships), (8) reaching out to online students (a rapidly growing demographic), (9) making sure students get answers to critical questions, (10) determining how student success is impacted by their high/low context disposition, learning style, 
personality type, and traditional ENG ASAP measures/activities, (11) collecting student data from CC partners using our ENG ASAP materials and assisting partners to maximally expose their scholars to ENG 
ASAP best practices, themes, activities and instruments. 
Generally, the struggle is associated with one or more of the following: picking a technical project 
area, getting started on the project, setting SMART goals, formulating a concrete problem for the project, 
staying on course, preparing for a career fair, researching companies, acquiring skills in job postings, career 
planning, finding a suitable mentor, preparing for graduate school, fully understanding the many 
opportunities before them and developing strategies and tactics to properly address them (e.g. pursuing 
funded/paid FURI/REU projects, senior design, internships, graduate school, fellowships).
